##What happened to the overseas Chinese in Italy, where the outbreak began?

Health insight

Functional introduction, understand the health professional news

* The latest figures show Italy has more than 7,000 confirmed cases and 366 deaths, making it the world's worst affected country after China.
* There are many overseas Chinese in Italy. When the epidemic broke out in Wuhan, they actively donated money and materials and swept away all the masks available in the area.
* Tai Lei's medical system failed to respond to the new pneumonia, and preventive measures were not in place. A local government refused to close a bar.
* The epidemic situation is becoming more and more serious. Some overseas Chinese want to return to their home countries to avoid danger, but they accidentally bring back diseases. Some overseas Chinese organizations have launched a call not to go back, so as not to add chaos to the country.

Italy has more than 7,000 confirmed cases and 366 deaths, making it the world's worst affected country after China, according to the latest figures.

The number of overseas Chinese in Italy is very large. When the epidemic broke out in Wuhan, they actively donated money and materials and swept away all the masks available in the area.

Italy's health care system has failed to deal with the disease, and anti-epidemic measures are not in place. A local government refused to close down a bar.

The overseas epidemic situation is getting worse and worse. Some overseas Chinese want to return to their home countries to avoid danger, but they accidentally bring back diseases. Some overseas Chinese organizations have launched a call not to go back, so as not to add chaos to the country.

When the domestic new crown epidemic situation was gradually controlled, the overseas epidemic situation has become the focus of attention. Official daily reports of the epidemic, there have been many cases of imported cases from overseas. As of March 7, China has reported a cumulative total of 63 imported confirmed cases.

Chen Hui, an overseas Chinese from Qingtian, Zhejiang Province, has lived in Italy for nine years, and his hometown of Milan is the worst affected area. From the early hours of March 8, the city of Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , where Milan is located, was placed in a red exclusion zone, barring all military police, medical and emergency personnel on duty. Outside Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , 14 other provinces have also been cordoned off. A quarter of Italy's population would be affected.

Italy followed the example of the Chinese city of Wuhan, a month and a half after its closure. Chen Hui said bluntly that he had experienced two rounds of the impact of the epidemic, once in China and once in Italy.

According to the latest figures, 7,375 cases have been confirmed in Italy, temporarily surpassing South Korea, which has the highest number of confirmed cases outside of China. And thousands of new cases a day, at an alarming rate. In particular, 366 new coronary patients have died in Italy, the second largest number in the world.

Chen Hui told the eight o'clock news about his experience since the outbreak of the epidemic. With regard to the situation of overseas Chinese, he hoped that his compatriots at home could look at it rationally and objectively.

Italians don't like masks

On February 23, local time in Italy, I decided to close the shop. The store, which opened in 2015 with a friend, is located in downtown Milan and sells computers, mobile phones and other electronic communication items. Milan is the economic capital of Italy, is also a tourist destination, so business has been good.

The reason for the closure was simple: On that day, the number of new confirmed cases in Italy soared to 215. That was an amazing number at the time. After all, there were only three new cases in Italy before Feb. 20, and all were diagnosed before Feb. 3. The number did not increase for 17 days, and everyone thought the epidemic was over.

So far, I haven't figured out why Europe's hardest hit region is in Italy. On January 30, Italy confirmed its first new case of the disease (a tourist from Wuhan) , and the next day prime minister Contes ordered all flights to and from China to be cut off, declaring a state of emergency. On February 23rd the Italian government closed 11 small towns in the regions of Lombardy and Veneto, the worst affected areas.

But the Italians have a big problem -- and perhaps the problem of all Europeans -- as Harvard did not like wearing masks. Even with more than 3,000 confirmed cases, when you go out on the streets of Milan, almost one in six people are wearing masks, and most of them are Asian.

This has to do with tradition. In 1975, Italy enacted a national law banning the wearing of masks, masks or masks in public places that might conceal a person's face. This is still the attitude of the Italian authorities in this case. The Italian Interior Ministry has a directive: Masks should be reserved for the sick, healthy people do not need to wear.

So, all the mainstream media are in the same line of thinking in the promotion of epidemic prevention measures, you can imagine, equivalent to the news broadcast told you, no symptoms can not wear a mask.

This kind of propaganda brings the very big negative effect to the non-governmental prevention and control work. In the early days of the outbreak, we went to the Cathedral in central Milan to hand out free masks, which few people would pick up. Ironically, just 30 meters from us, a lot of Italians got together to sing and dance... and then we gave up and thought about isolating ourselves at home.

My neighbor, an elderly couple in their 60s, was the more anxious of the locals, who instinctively feared that the new deaths in Italy were almost invariably elderly. At first they didn't wear masks, and often asked me why do you Chinese wear masks? What's the use of masks? After I gave them a general explanation, they put on their masks incredulously.

Italy also has a very bad place, although the early cut off flights with China, but the airport basically no prevention and control measures, do not take the temperature will not ask. This lax regulation could easily lead to bigger problems, especially since Italy is a member of the Schengen Convention, which allows it to move freely between all 26 countries with any one Schengen Identity Card or visa.

It's a dangerous thing to do. The first four cases in Brazil all came from Italy.

The Milanese have been forced to lose their grace

For the Italian overseas Chinese, these 40 days, it is equivalent to two outbreaks. Once for China, once for this side.

When we had the outbreak in January, our hearts were gripped. On the one hand, we all have families back home. On the other hand, it was only after I had gone abroad that I realized that it was more patriotic to be in a foreign country.

At that stage, in addition to constantly refreshing the news, we can do is to donate supplies. In Large European cities, there are local overseas Chinese associations. Most of US donate to these associations and they organize the purchase of supplies. I personally donated about 40,000 RMB, not much, can only be said to be within our means. A woman I know from Qingtian, born after 1985, was in Milan doing the purchasing business. She went to Switzerland to order several boxes of N95 masks and sent them back to China. Then there was the Chinese who suddenly sold out a Milan pharmacy's 10-year supply of face masks, an event that eventually made the news.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Delta survey respondents

The Italians will be a bit shocked at first, but the idea is that you can buy what you want, it's your freedom, we just have to negotiate the price. Later, several of our friends also analyzed it, which is probably one of the reasons why the Italian Interior Ministry didn't recommend wearing masks, because by the time the outbreak of the disease broke out in Italy, masks were almost impossible to buy here. If the government at this time that masks are very important, but can not buy, it will cause public resentment.

Some of the materials we donate to China will be sent to Wuhan, and some will be sent to our hometown. I remember a new word on the Internet at that time called "suicide aid, " to the effect that Zhejiang Province donated materials to Wuhan crazily, only to find that hospitals in the province were also in short supply. On the one hand, we overseas Chinese from Zhejiang are very proud, on the other hand, we are also very distressed, so we will send some of the materials back to Zhejiang. The girl mentioned earlier, the mask she bought was sent back to Qingtian and Hangzhou.

I personally donated 1,888 yuan to the account of the Charity Association of Wuhan in the hope that things would go well. The next day after I made the payment, I was so angry that I had to read about the inaction of the local charity. I didn't understand that one when I used profanity directly on my social media account.

Unexpectedly, a month later, Italy also staged a panic buying wave, I also became a witness. It was Friday, February 28, and I was out shopping at a local supermarket chain. I was dumbfounded when I arrived at the supermarket. Almost all the things on the shelves were cleared out. Later, I saw a staff member with a cart of meat ready to load, at least 20 boxes, he has not pushed to the shelf side, the meat has been robbed. That day, the looters were mostly Asian.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The next day, the supermarket was empty again, this time the main force has become Italian locals, they are afraid not to rob again. Later, I heard from more than one Italian that they never thought they'd have to go to the supermarket to get supplies. The Milanese are, by their very nature, very graceful, very good at enjoying life, very slow in everything they do, and I think it's incredible that they are forced to do this.

The government won't close the shop for the locals'breakfast

There are many overseas Chinese in Italy, including 100,000 from Qingtian. This whole time, we've actually been in fear.

Italy now has two hard hit areas, both in the north. One is Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , with Milan as its capital, and the other is Veneto, with Venice as its capital. The first imported case to come to light in Zhejiang Province was a restaurant in Province of Bergamo, Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. , less than 50 kilometers from where I live in Milan.

I don't know the Wang Lady, but we're both from Qingtian. From what I've heard, she had a fever on February 16th and saw a doctor in Italy, but the doctor thought it was just a common cold, gave her two antipyretics, told her to drink plenty of water, and sent her home. She may have thought it was bad (because she runs a restaurant and is in daily contact with a lot of people) and decided to go home without proper medical treatment.

This condition is common in the Italian medical system, where doctors are ineffective in treating patients with mild illnesses. I had a similar situation in Milan when I went to the doctor with a fever and a cold and he would say, 'wait a minute, let me finish my cup of coffee. That's fine in normal times, but when a pandemic strikes, their doctors can't handle it, and their health authorities don't have the capacity to mobilize multiple resources.

A few days ago, an Italian hospital and a hospital in Wuhan held a video conference, Italian doctors asked a question said that doctors in the ward to wear surgical masks or N95 masks. You See, even these basic precautions aren't clear. And as far as I know, Milan has opened a total of four new crown designated hospitals, including one in the military, and now a large number of medical staff have been infected, which is a terrible thing.

The other thing is even scarier. You're not gonNA believe this.

I have a friend who owns a bar in a small town in the south of Qingtian, about 15 minutes from the red zone. Not long ago, because of the outbreak, he applied to the local government to suspend business, but was denied, on the grounds that if the shop closed, the town's residents would have no place to eat breakfast. So now he's got to wear a mask every day and walk around the store looking over his shoulder.

This is in stark contrast to the isolation of domestic "scorched earth" . Under such circumstances, I don't think there is an overseas Chinese who doesn't want to go back home.

Don't put the overseas Chinese in the position of "being unkind and unjust" 

In recent days, I have seen a lot of comments on the Internet about overseas Chinese returning to China, especially after eight overseas Chinese from Qingtian, Italy, were diagnosed with new pneumonia, as if the group of overseas Chinese had been nailed to a post of injustice.

I'd like to say a few words of my own.

First of all, there are two concepts must be clear, overseas Chinese and ethnic Chinese are not the same. The overseas Chinese are Chinese. We Use People's Republic of China passports and live abroad only for work or study. We are domiciled in our own country and are covered by social security, so it is not as if we are "a bunch of foreigners taking up our medical resources" as many claim.

Secondly, I can understand the frustration of those eight Qingtian Boys. When we saw the news that hundreds of Chinese nationals were evacuated from Iran by chartered domestic flights, all of them liked it, and I was no exception, this was certainly the best way. But 10 days ago, did the eight overseas Chinese in Qingtian ever have such an opportunity? They're just trying to keep themselves safe.

Of course, their approach is open to question, such as whether the relevant authorities in the country were notified in advance, whether strict protection was provided on the way home, and whether the relevant regulations were enforced upon return. I am not opposed to discussing or even criticizing these specific issues, but I do not agree with the indiscriminate stigmatization of the overseas Chinese community.

Both the 10 imported cases in Zhejiang and the 60 in China are only a small fraction of overseas Chinese.

In recent days, Qingtian's hometown association in Milan has begun mapping out the situation and formed a wechat group. A group of 500 people, has been formed more than 10, about 6,000 people. The person in charge of the overseas Chinese Group placates everyone in the group. If nothing happens, don't go back. Going back will also add chaos to the country. Everyone listens very much. In fact, it is also true that the overseas Chinese around me, including me, have no plans to return home.

What for? There's no less risk of infection on the way back, 14 days of quarantine, no telling when we'll be back. Business is still here.

The Italian government's recent pledge to spend $5bn on a pandemic is a sign of real determination in a country with a big budget deficit. In addition, China has also started to Italy's material assistance and technical support. We believe that in the face of unity and goodwill, the disease will eventually be overcome.

(the name Chen Hui in the article is an alias)
